WEBVTT

00:00.933 --> 00:03.302
[Gabby] One spoonbill chick
fell from the nest.

00:03.304 --> 00:05.804
[Francis] I would say I'm
definitely pretty close with Sterling.

00:05.806 --> 00:09.274
I love that noise. [laughs]
How are you, handsome?

00:09.276 --> 00:13.579
He's pretty affectionate cause he spent more
time with us, than with other spoonbills.

00:13.581 --> 00:16.782
- Thanks buddy.
- [bird quacks]

00:16.784 --> 00:20.919
<i>[Micah] Working with snakes was probably
the part that I was most nervous about.</i>

00:20.921 --> 00:24.423
<i>But over time, it's my
favorite part of the job.</i>

00:24.425 --> 00:27.426
You do have to be careful
working with these snakes, for sure.

00:29.095 --> 00:32.765
<i>[Sara] Currently we have one male
Matschie's tree-kangaroo at the Bronx.</i>

00:32.767 --> 00:35.067
Hey Handsome.
His name is Artemis.

00:35.069 --> 00:36.602
<i>So we're getting in
a new female.</i>

00:36.604 --> 00:39.238
<i>Hopefully we'll be able to
put them together on exhibit.</i>

00:39.240 --> 00:42.508
We'll see how it goes!
I hope he's excited. [laughs]

00:45.412 --> 00:47.980
<i>[Jim] If you ask a child
to draw a picture of a zoo,</i>

00:47.982 --> 00:51.116
<i>chances are they'll draw
an animal behind bars.</i>

00:51.118 --> 00:54.486
We've gotta take that image
and change it.

00:54.488 --> 00:58.323
They really enjoy this. It strengthens
the bond that we have with these guys.

00:59.125 --> 01:01.126
Come on. I know.
You don't like doors.

01:01.128 --> 01:02.828
[woman] Go on ladies!

01:02.830 --> 01:05.964
<i>[Jim] It's not enough to keep animals
in exhibits just for people to look at.</i>

01:05.966 --> 01:07.900
<i>There has to be
a higher purpose.</i>

01:07.902 --> 01:11.203
<i>And for us, it's conservation
of species in the wild.</i>

01:11.205 --> 01:12.771
[man] Are we rolling?

01:13.073 --> 01:15.774
<i>[Jim] The general public would
never get the access you're gonna get.</i>

01:15.776 --> 01:17.309
[woman] Good Girl!

01:17.311 --> 01:20.913
<i>[Jim] Which is to see what goes
on behind the scenes, everyday.</i>

01:20.915 --> 01:23.115
That's how we do it here
in the Boogie Down Bronx.

01:23.117 --> 01:24.349
[laughter]

01:34.527 --> 01:36.462
- [child] Hello monkey!
- [camera shutter clicks]

01:40.066 --> 01:41.700
[Sara]
So, we're in Jungle World,

01:41.702 --> 01:45.003
on our way
to the tree kangaroo holding.

01:45.005 --> 01:48.707
Currently we have one male
Matschie's tree-kangaroo at the Bronx.

01:48.709 --> 01:50.209
His name is Artemis.

01:51.177 --> 01:55.214
<i>He was actually born here
and he is about 13 years old,</i>

01:55.216 --> 01:59.184
so I guess middle aged
is a good way of putting it.

01:59.186 --> 02:03.055
<i>He's still very active,
very curious, adventurous.</i>

02:04.124 --> 02:06.024
<i>He's a really cool animal
to work with.</i>

02:06.960 --> 02:09.161
We're gonna be doing
some basic behaviors.

02:09.163 --> 02:11.663
So we got all of this
training supplies.

02:12.899 --> 02:16.135
Hey handsome. Watch your paws.

02:16.137 --> 02:19.271
I think the first thing when
anyone looks at a tree kangaroo,

02:19.273 --> 02:21.039
is just how cute they are.

02:21.041 --> 02:22.341
They look like
a little teddy bear.

02:22.343 --> 02:23.675
Come on down.

02:25.078 --> 02:27.146
Good job honey bun.

02:28.681 --> 02:31.683
<i>The Matschie's tree-kangaroos
are a little smaller</i>

02:31.685 --> 02:34.253
<i>than what you think of
when you think of kangaroos.</i>

02:34.255 --> 02:38.557
<i>They are found in a forested
area in Papa New Guinea.</i>

02:39.526 --> 02:41.460
Artemis, come get this.

02:44.998 --> 02:46.498
There ya go.

02:46.500 --> 02:49.968
<i>I've been working with the tree
kangaroos, just under ten years.</i>

02:49.970 --> 02:52.604
<i>With Artemis,
if I wasn't bonded with him,</i>

02:52.606 --> 02:55.941
he wouldn't let me do
any of the tactiles.

02:55.943 --> 02:59.678
And it definitely takes a while for
you to build up that level of trust.

03:01.147 --> 03:02.648
Whatcha doin'?

03:02.650 --> 03:05.317
<i>It makes me really appreciate
the relationship I have,</i>

03:05.319 --> 03:09.388
knowing that he'll let me do
things that not everyone gets to do.

03:10.423 --> 03:13.358
And he's all set
to go out on exhibit today.

03:14.160 --> 03:16.528
There ya go, buddy.

03:18.364 --> 03:20.065
He does not hesitate.

03:22.335 --> 03:25.037
And now we'll just go upstairs
and check him out.

03:25.039 --> 03:26.972
Make sure he's doing all right
out there.

03:28.975 --> 03:32.377
So, Artemis lives in the
first Jungle World exhibit.

03:32.379 --> 03:36.415
And as you can see, he
lives with Rodrigues fruit bats.

03:36.417 --> 03:38.850
Sometimes they come down
and steal his breakfast.

03:38.852 --> 03:42.120
But they usually fly away
when they see him comin'.

03:43.089 --> 03:45.257
And he is a solitary animal.

03:45.259 --> 03:47.926
A lot of people ask us
why he's here all by himself.

03:47.928 --> 03:49.361
That's how
they live in the wild.

03:49.363 --> 03:53.465
They come together for breeding
and then they kind of separate

03:53.467 --> 03:54.600
and live their own lives.

03:57.537 --> 04:00.272
We're getting in a new female
which is really exciting.

04:00.274 --> 04:02.808
Hopefully we will be able to
put them together at some point,

04:02.810 --> 04:04.943
to allow them to breed.

04:04.945 --> 04:09.281
We'll see how it goes, but it's
exciting and I hope he's excited.

04:09.283 --> 04:10.582
[laughs]

04:22.962 --> 04:24.896
[Micah] I'm heading over
to the health center

04:24.898 --> 04:27.599
to take care of some
Mang pit vipers that we have.

04:28.668 --> 04:31.270
<i>Last summer we had
a pretty large confiscation</i>

04:31.272 --> 04:33.438
<i>of a number of venomous snakes.</i>

04:33.440 --> 04:36.341
<i>[Jesse] We had a gentleman who's bit
by a venomous snake over the weekend.</i>

04:36.343 --> 04:38.510
<i>After speaking with him,</i>

04:38.512 --> 04:41.446
we found out that he had
a lot more snakes in his home.

04:41.448 --> 04:46.118
<i>[Jim] This is crazy. We were told that
there was approximately 50 snakes.</i>

04:46.120 --> 04:47.919
<i>Now, when we got here
on site today,</i>

04:47.921 --> 04:51.490
we heard that there may be
at least twice that many.

04:51.492 --> 04:54.693
[Micah] These two mang vipers
are still here.

04:54.695 --> 04:56.895
And today we have some rats
for them to eat.

04:56.897 --> 04:59.097
So, I bet they'll be
pretty excited about that.

04:59.099 --> 05:01.066
All these snakes are venomous.

05:02.502 --> 05:06.571
So, you do have to be careful
working these snakes, for sure.

05:07.907 --> 05:10.275
The two snakes
I'll be working with today are

05:10.277 --> 05:13.779
female here and a male
right in front of me.

05:13.781 --> 05:16.848
They're two
Mang Mountain vipers.

05:16.850 --> 05:21.787
Mang Mountain vipers are a species
of pit viper found in forests in China.

05:21.789 --> 05:24.189
They can reach pretty far
when they strike.

05:24.191 --> 05:26.692
Most snakes have a strike
range somewhere in one third,

05:26.694 --> 05:28.093
to one half their body length.

05:28.095 --> 05:30.696
So, if you have
a six foot snake,

05:30.698 --> 05:34.466
you have to imagine that they have somewhere
between two and three feet of reach.

05:49.215 --> 05:50.949
That went all right.

05:52.251 --> 05:56.788
I really never imagined I'd be
doing something like this as my job.

05:56.790 --> 05:59.224
After working here
for a period of time,

05:59.226 --> 06:02.394
I actually enjoyed working
with venomous snakes so much

06:02.396 --> 06:04.763
that I decided
to get a tattoo of one.

06:04.765 --> 06:06.164
The timber rattlesnake,

06:06.166 --> 06:10.035
which is a native venomous
snake species to New York.

06:10.037 --> 06:13.438
I started out really nervous
to do this job.

06:14.073 --> 06:15.707
But I committed to it.

06:15.709 --> 06:21.079
<i>And I spent a lot of time learning,
asking questions, asking for help.</i>

06:21.081 --> 06:25.016
<i>And committing
to do the best that I can.</i>

06:25.018 --> 06:26.985
It's nice to have that reminder.

06:28.254 --> 06:31.323
Right now these two Mang
Mountain vipers are living here,

06:31.325 --> 06:33.258
at the health center.

06:33.260 --> 06:36.461
But, we're working on a new
exhibit for them over at Reptile House.

06:36.463 --> 06:38.163
[drill whirring]

06:38.165 --> 06:41.400
[Emily] So, this is gonna have
a ceramic bulb in it

06:41.402 --> 06:45.837
that will radiate
so the whole rock will be hot.

06:45.839 --> 06:50.308
Which is why though we had to
change it from epoxy to cement.

06:50.310 --> 06:52.878
Most snakes
love basking on hot rocks.

06:52.880 --> 06:54.880
But from what I've read
about this guy,

06:54.882 --> 06:57.349
he likes the cold
and then hot rocks.

06:58.885 --> 07:02.387
They'll be moving from these separate
enclosures, into an exhibit together.

07:02.389 --> 07:05.157
Which gives them the
opportunity to potentially breed.

07:05.159 --> 07:06.625
Which'd be
really exciting for us.

07:06.627 --> 07:08.860
So hopefully in the near future,

07:08.862 --> 07:11.430
we'll be moving them over and
have them on view for the public.

07:11.432 --> 07:14.433
And I think it'll be a great opportunity
for people to see these snakes

07:14.435 --> 07:16.034
and learn more about them.

07:18.905 --> 07:21.306
- [children chatting]
- Over here!

07:22.341 --> 07:23.942
He's waggin' his tail.

07:26.112 --> 07:30.415
[Gabby] I'm doing my AM check
and AM feed in the marsh exhibit.

07:33.453 --> 07:35.654
[whistles]

07:38.825 --> 07:42.194
- [birds chirp]
- [whistles]

07:43.196 --> 07:47.766
We have a group
of African spoonbills,

07:47.768 --> 07:52.704
and they are a species of bird
that's native to regions of Africa.

07:52.706 --> 07:59.277
And as their name suggests, their
bill is almost shaped like a spoon.

07:59.279 --> 08:07.279
This year we've had a number of
spoonbill chicks hatch out in this exhibit.

08:07.421 --> 08:13.692
One chick fell from the nest and was
taken to World Birds and the Brita Room

08:13.694 --> 08:16.094
where the keepers there
are raising it.

08:19.165 --> 08:21.433
[Francis] He's gonna get some
slop, some chopped fish,

08:21.435 --> 08:23.368
some meat balls.
These ones are his favorite.

08:23.370 --> 08:25.437
And we're gonna grab him
a water bowl as well.

08:26.939 --> 08:28.139
Hi, Sterling!

08:29.041 --> 08:31.977
- Hey buddy.
- [bird quacks]

08:31.979 --> 08:35.046
This is Sterling. He's only
a couple of months old.

08:35.048 --> 08:37.349
So, he's just a baby.

08:37.351 --> 08:39.684
Sterling was found
tossed from his nest.

08:39.686 --> 08:44.256
In the case where a bird lays
more than one egg,

08:44.258 --> 08:48.360
the parents might reject the egg or
the hatchling for whatever reason.

08:48.362 --> 08:49.928
<i>This is something natural
that happens.</i>

08:49.930 --> 08:54.666
<i>The babies themselves also might
toss each other, in competitiveness.</i>

08:54.668 --> 08:58.069
<i>This is one of the reasons why we keep
a close eye on nests and on hatchlings,</i>

08:58.071 --> 09:02.140
in order to be able
to intervene if we're needed.

09:02.142 --> 09:05.911
He's pretty affectionate cause
he spent more time with us

09:05.913 --> 09:09.147
than with other spoonbills
and is pretty personable.

09:09.149 --> 09:11.683
It's definitely nice
to start a day with an animal

09:11.685 --> 09:14.386
whose just as happy to see you
as you are to see them.

09:15.855 --> 09:17.689
All right, come on Sterling.

09:17.691 --> 09:19.291
Time to clean up. Good boy.

09:19.859 --> 09:21.259
There ya go.

09:22.228 --> 09:24.963
<i>We change out those mats
every morning.</i>

09:24.965 --> 09:27.299
<i>Give his enclosure
a little hose down.</i>

09:27.301 --> 09:29.568
<i>And it gives him a good chance
to get some exercise as well.</i>

09:31.370 --> 09:34.539
There we go! Yeah.

09:35.675 --> 09:37.042
There you go.

09:37.810 --> 09:40.078
A lot of young birds
will do stuff like this.

09:40.080 --> 09:43.348
Kinda catching gusts of wind
to help build up muscles

09:43.350 --> 09:45.584
that will actually
help carry them in flight.

09:45.586 --> 09:47.686
<i>It's an interesting
predicament because,</i>

09:47.688 --> 09:52.691
we would always prefer that an animal
be able to be with others of its own kind.

09:52.693 --> 09:54.893
<i>But he's more accustomed
to being around us,</i>

09:54.895 --> 09:57.228
then he would be
around his own family.

09:57.230 --> 09:59.664
I would say I'm definitely
pretty close with Sterling.

09:59.666 --> 10:04.102
At this stage his feathers and my
hair probably feel about the same.

10:04.104 --> 10:08.039
He'll groom my eyebrows, he likes all the
little things that he can kinda get over--

10:08.041 --> 10:09.441
Get through his bill.

10:10.109 --> 10:11.609
Thanks buddy.

10:11.611 --> 10:14.679
I've been interested in animals
basically, since before I could speak.

10:14.681 --> 10:17.082
<i>I remember coming here
to the zoo as a kid</i>

10:17.084 --> 10:19.317
and saying like,
I want to be there someday.

10:19.319 --> 10:21.886
And so it's really great
to be able to be here

10:21.888 --> 10:25.991
and then to also have such a unique
experience with an animal like Sterling.

10:26.659 --> 10:28.326
All right. You ready?

10:30.529 --> 10:32.297
There you go.

10:32.299 --> 10:35.800
He's gonna ruin all my hard
work and make a big mess.

10:35.802 --> 10:38.670
Some possibilities is, he could
go back to our aquatic bird house

10:38.672 --> 10:41.573
and be with other spoonbills,
or he could go on to become

10:41.575 --> 10:44.342
an ambassador animal
here at the zoo.

10:44.344 --> 10:48.380
In a case where you are hand raising
an animal, they might learn behaviors

10:48.382 --> 10:52.083
that are not quite spoonbill
behaviors, for example.

10:52.085 --> 10:55.220
So he might not be able
to connect with other birds.

10:55.222 --> 10:57.722
<i>That's something
that we do have to monitor.</i>

10:57.724 --> 11:01.960
All right. I gotta go.
Bye-bye, baby.

11:03.529 --> 11:08.133
So we finally got our rock for
our Mang vipers. It looks awesome.

11:08.135 --> 11:10.835
[Micah] I think it'll be really
exciting to see what our brand-new

11:10.837 --> 11:14.039
Mang Mountain viper exhibit looks
like once this paper comes down.

11:15.841 --> 11:19.177
We're getting ready to receive
the young female tree kangaroo.

11:19.179 --> 11:22.414
[Jessica] Hi, Artemis!
You got a girlfriend.

11:27.153 --> 11:30.021
The turtle! Look at him.

11:37.329 --> 11:40.432
<i>[Micah] This section of the reptile
house is what we call North Passage.</i>

11:40.434 --> 11:43.601
<i>What I'm trying to do is
just see where everyone is,</i>

11:43.603 --> 11:46.571
<i>make sure everyone looks
healthy in their exhibit.</i>

11:49.375 --> 11:55.046
This will be the location of our
brand-new Mang Mountain viper exhibit.

11:55.048 --> 11:57.382
So, the exhibit's chap is
still building the rock work

11:57.384 --> 11:59.084
that's gonna go in this exhibit.

11:59.086 --> 12:01.920
And then painting and so, I
think it'll be really exciting to see

12:01.922 --> 12:03.988
what is looks like
once this paper comes down.

12:03.990 --> 12:08.460
<i>To be able to give these two
individual animals this new space,</i>

12:08.462 --> 12:11.129
it's really satisfying and I
know it's just two snakes,

12:11.131 --> 12:13.465
but that feels really great.

12:13.933 --> 12:16.067
[golf cart beeping]

12:19.271 --> 12:21.172
[Emily] I've been working
on some new features

12:21.174 --> 12:24.542
for the Mang Mountain viper
exhibit at Reptile House.

12:24.544 --> 12:27.612
And we are installing
the rock feature.

12:29.482 --> 12:31.049
Oh, geez.

12:35.488 --> 12:37.322
<i>I totally did some nerding out.</i>

12:37.324 --> 12:40.725
Researching where they live,
the habitat.

12:40.727 --> 12:44.362
<i>It's like this very specific region
of the Hunan province in China.</i>

12:44.364 --> 12:48.066
<i>I used that as the basis
for making the rock.</i>

12:50.803 --> 12:53.905
<i>It feels really good to see
your work go on exhibit</i>

12:53.907 --> 12:57.509
because you're not only
improving the animals' habitat,

12:57.511 --> 12:59.844
you're enhancing
viewer experience

12:59.846 --> 13:03.314
<i>and you're doing your part for
conservation and that's really great.</i>

13:04.884 --> 13:08.787
This mural is two-dimensional,
but we try to make it

13:08.789 --> 13:12.590
look as three-dimensional
and as expansive as possible.

13:16.962 --> 13:20.799
We want to get it as close
to their natural habitat.

13:20.801 --> 13:25.336
So when I painted, I painted
mostly like, facing this way.

13:25.338 --> 13:28.439
Because I know the viewer is
going to mostly be looking this way.

13:30.342 --> 13:34.212
Looking forward to the moment
when they are in the exhibit.

13:34.214 --> 13:37.682
And see if they
like the heated rock.

13:37.684 --> 13:41.519
Hopefully they feel at home
in their space here.

13:47.927 --> 13:50.094
- [woman] Hello!
- [child] Hello!

13:51.130 --> 13:52.997
- [Brandon] What do you think?
- [Sara] I like that one.

13:52.999 --> 13:54.532
- [Brandon] Yeah.
- [Sara] And then this one,

13:54.534 --> 13:57.435
- might be the perfect height for one of those shelves.
- [Brandon] Okay.

13:57.437 --> 13:59.838
[Sara] And that'll also
give her some sitting option.

13:59.840 --> 14:01.339
- Yeah.
- [chainsaw whirring]

14:04.877 --> 14:06.477
All right.
I'll meet you in there.

14:08.113 --> 14:11.115
<i>[Brandon] We're getting ready to
receive a young female tree kangaroo</i>

14:11.117 --> 14:13.351
<i>from the
San Diego Zoo Safari Park.</i>

14:13.353 --> 14:15.053
[Sara] Comin' through!

14:15.055 --> 14:16.855
<i>[Brandon] Today we're getting
her enclosure ready,</i>

14:16.857 --> 14:20.158
were putting together
what we call 'perching'.

14:20.160 --> 14:24.128
<i>Tree kangaroos are arboreal. So,
we like to provide them with something</i>

14:24.130 --> 14:28.867
<i>that's somewhat close to what
they would be climbing on in the wild.</i>

14:28.869 --> 14:33.671
<i>It's not an exhibit space, so we're
not as concerned with the aesthetics.</i>

14:33.673 --> 14:35.340
<i>It's more just
the functionality.</i>

14:35.342 --> 14:37.408
<i>Just to give her some options.</i>

14:39.345 --> 14:41.679
[Sara] I know
she likes to be up high.

14:41.681 --> 14:44.282
So I was wondering if maybe
we could get something from here,

14:44.284 --> 14:46.918
- to like an anchor up there?
- Sure. Yeah.

14:46.920 --> 14:48.586
We gotta get it right,
just for her.

14:49.855 --> 14:52.724
I like it cause she has a
little bit of a seat right there.

14:52.726 --> 14:54.459
I think she's gonna love it.

14:56.228 --> 15:00.531
I'm really pleased. So all that's
left now is just the kangaroo.

15:16.248 --> 15:17.615
- Thanks.
- Yep.

15:19.084 --> 15:21.920
[Jessica] <i>Matschie's tree-kangaroos
are listed as endangered.</i>

15:21.922 --> 15:25.023
<i>Like pretty much all tropical
forest dwelling species,</i>

15:25.025 --> 15:27.625
they're threatened
by hunting and habitat loss.

15:27.627 --> 15:29.994
<i>So, it's really exciting
to have Polly here,</i>

15:29.996 --> 15:35.199
<i>because it's been a while since
we've had a breeding situation here.</i>

15:36.936 --> 15:41.272
<i>I hope that her and Artemis get along
really well. And I hope that they breed.</i>

15:42.074 --> 15:46.044
Hi, Artemis!
You got a girlfriend.

15:46.046 --> 15:49.113
<i>You know, the fact that we
do have that possibility now</i>

15:49.115 --> 15:52.283
<i>means that, you know, we have a
better chance of continuing to maintain</i>

15:52.285 --> 15:54.218
<i>the species
here at the Bronx Zoo.</i>

15:56.455 --> 15:57.622
Hey, sweetie.

16:06.565 --> 16:08.199
There she goes.

16:09.501 --> 16:12.937
[laughs] Hi, sweetie!

16:14.206 --> 16:15.539
How was your flight?

16:20.813 --> 16:25.183
[Sara] It's really exciting, not
only just have a new animal but,

16:25.185 --> 16:28.052
one of the animals that I
get to work with pretty closely.

16:31.957 --> 16:37.462
I like how calm she seems. And comfortable
to get around in a new enclosure.

16:39.331 --> 16:43.267
It's always stressful on some
level for an animal arriving

16:43.269 --> 16:46.304
<i>in a new facility, totally new
surroundings, new people.</i>

16:46.306 --> 16:49.140
<i>So, we will just
