17:00.719 --> 17:02.320
I love seeing her using that.

17:03.389 --> 17:04.622
[Sara] Hi, sweet princess!

17:05.858 --> 17:08.393
[Lauren] This is an artificial
sloth tree.

17:09.294 --> 17:10.895
It's just about done.

17:10.897 --> 17:12.330
She's like, all right,
I like this.

17:12.831 --> 17:14.332
[Kathleen] You got it, girl.

17:16.168 --> 17:20.071
Come on out buddy. There you
go. Come on, come over here.

17:20.073 --> 17:23.508
[Kathleen] The first thing I always
look for, someone that needs a home.

17:23.510 --> 17:25.176
- Good morning!
- Hi! How are you?

17:25.178 --> 17:26.978
We got a friend for ya.

17:41.193 --> 17:44.228
We're gonna go get Calisto,
our two toed sloth.

17:49.001 --> 17:50.368
Good girl.

17:50.370 --> 17:52.837
Calisto enjoys
going to the classroom,

17:52.839 --> 17:55.606
she actually likes being held
like this too. [laughs]

17:56.475 --> 17:58.376
Today we have our sloth
encounter

17:58.378 --> 18:00.344
and we'll be featuring Calisto.

18:00.346 --> 18:02.113
- [gasps]
- [laughter]

18:03.882 --> 18:07.118
She's so nice that, if you guys
want to come up you can pet her.

18:07.120 --> 18:08.886
Our sloth encounters,

18:08.888 --> 18:11.289
they're one of the most
popular encounters we have.

18:11.291 --> 18:13.758
So you're gonna pet her
right on her back.

18:13.760 --> 18:16.527
- Oh my gosh!
- [gasp]

18:16.529 --> 18:19.163
<i>[Kathleen] We've always shown
a sloth on a coat rack.</i>

18:19.165 --> 18:22.366
<i>We would roll it around
outside if we did encounters,</i>

18:22.368 --> 18:24.335
<i>or in the classrooms
that we've used.</i>

18:24.337 --> 18:26.437
- Thank you.
- Yeah, no problem!

18:26.439 --> 18:30.341
So we started thinking about something
prettier, more naturalistic looking.

18:30.343 --> 18:34.445
<i>We sent Lauren some pictures
of sloths in the wild.</i>

18:34.447 --> 18:37.148
<i>And she came up
with this wonderful design.</i>

18:37.150 --> 18:40.284
<i>It's a beautiful tree
for our sloth.</i>

18:40.286 --> 18:44.388
[Lauren] This is an artificial
sloth tree for the TAB building.

18:44.390 --> 18:48.326
I did take impressions of an
actual tree to create a pad,

18:48.328 --> 18:51.496
to replicate
the texture of bark.

18:51.498 --> 18:56.367
It's just about done, I'm just
testing out fitting it on the base.

18:56.369 --> 18:58.402
And then it's ready
to be delivered.

18:59.805 --> 19:02.006
I'm pretty proud of this piece.

19:02.008 --> 19:04.942
I love sloths and I think
that kids and adults

19:04.944 --> 19:09.413
will really enjoy interacting
with a sloth on this tree.

19:12.484 --> 19:14.919
[Kira] All right, so which one are
we thinking? This one right here?

19:14.921 --> 19:16.420
Go with your gut,
wherever you think.

19:16.422 --> 19:19.690
-I feel this one. What're you feelin' Calisto?
-That's what we'd do.

19:19.692 --> 19:21.225
She's like,
all right, I like this.

19:22.094 --> 19:23.461
[Kathleen] You got it, girl.

19:24.830 --> 19:27.398
I mean think about it, in the wild
they have to do this you know?

19:27.400 --> 19:30.168
Test a branch,
can it support their weight?

19:30.170 --> 19:31.302
I'm still
a little nervous just--

19:31.304 --> 19:33.538
- Right, you wanna just...
- [laughter]

19:33.540 --> 19:38.242
[Lauren] It's probably like the first time
you see your kid on a bike or something.

19:38.244 --> 19:40.244
[laughter]

19:40.246 --> 19:43.214
[Lauren] Everything that was
put into this tree absolutely paid off.

19:43.216 --> 19:45.049
You know,
this is the rewarding part.

19:45.051 --> 19:50.188
To actually be able to create
something to make their lives better.

19:50.190 --> 19:52.123
[Kathleen] Each time we
have her out here

19:52.125 --> 19:54.425
her comfort level
is going to increase.

19:54.427 --> 19:57.261
One day she's gonna be
asleep right here.

19:57.896 --> 19:59.530
And that's gonna be really nice.

20:04.503 --> 20:08.439
- Look at, up there!
- Oh my gosh! Whoa!

20:12.311 --> 20:14.078
Sorry buddy.

20:16.181 --> 20:19.016
We're here in the
tree kangaroo exhibit,

20:19.018 --> 20:22.486
I'm just going to pick up any
old food and set out fresh food.

20:24.389 --> 20:27.558
All right.
So the exhibit is all ready.

20:27.560 --> 20:29.293
We just need a kangaroo.

20:37.035 --> 20:38.402
Go ahead buddy!

20:38.404 --> 20:40.705
There you go. Good job.

20:51.984 --> 20:56.053
I'm just grabbing some of the
greens that are in Polly's diet.

20:56.055 --> 20:58.923
Her diet's a little different
than what we feed Artemis.

20:58.925 --> 21:01.158
You can imagine
California, New York,

21:01.160 --> 21:03.094
have quite different
plant species growing.

21:03.096 --> 21:06.163
So what I have here is
a little bit of banana leaf

21:06.165 --> 21:09.934
and some... a couple different
kinds of honeysuckle brows.

21:09.936 --> 21:12.703
And we have her diet
all set by her holding,

21:12.705 --> 21:15.106
so we'll go down
and give her, her breakfast.

21:18.076 --> 21:21.279
Polly has been here
for just over two weeks.

21:21.281 --> 21:25.016
Today, I'll be hand feeding
Polly, doing a little socializing.

21:25.018 --> 21:29.020
Hand feeding Polly is something we
do just to build a bond with the animals

21:29.022 --> 21:33.324
<i>before we do any training. Make sure
that they'll actually take food from us.</i>

21:33.326 --> 21:37.561
You know, a sign of trust from them
that they'll accept their diet from you.

21:37.563 --> 21:40.398
And that they are comfortable
with you being that close to them.

21:42.601 --> 21:44.268
Hi, sweet princess.

21:46.204 --> 21:52.443
She has started taking things like greens
and leaves, carrots have been a big hit.

21:52.445 --> 21:57.048
With Polly specifically, I've been
able to speak with some of her keepers

21:57.050 --> 22:01.519
<i>from San Diego for things like
her diet, her behavior,</i>

22:01.521 --> 22:04.455
things that she likes to do
for enrichment.

22:04.457 --> 22:07.625
<i>You're never quite sure what
that animal's gonna prefer.</i>

22:07.627 --> 22:10.161
I'm with you girl.
I love green beans.

22:11.863 --> 22:15.933
So pretty much every morning I've been
spending 15 minutes or so in here with her.

22:15.935 --> 22:19.036
Kinda handing her
different food items.

22:19.038 --> 22:22.106
This is not something that we would've
been able to do a couple weeks ago.

22:22.108 --> 22:24.141
So, she's making improvements.

22:26.812 --> 22:29.246
<i>She still has another
two weeks in quarantine.</i>

22:29.248 --> 22:33.818
And once she finishes that up,
and everything's clear for her

22:33.820 --> 22:36.987
<i>she'll start introductions
with our male, Artemis.</i>

22:38.023 --> 22:40.124
Good news,
I found another green bean.

22:41.259 --> 22:44.295
- Jackpot, I know!
- [crunching]

22:49.835 --> 22:52.036
Whoa! See the little babies?

22:55.774 --> 22:57.842
[Jim] I'm headed over
to the World of Birds

22:57.844 --> 23:04.081
because there's an African spoonbill
chick that the keepers are raising.

23:04.083 --> 23:08.119
It might be a good candidate
to join Kathleen's program

23:08.121 --> 23:10.221
because it's pretty imprinted
on people.

23:12.958 --> 23:14.792
- Hi guys.
- Hey, Sir, how are you?

23:14.794 --> 23:17.061
- Good. How are you?
- We're good. We're very good.

23:17.063 --> 23:19.897
- Did you go in yet?
- No we wanted to wait for you.

23:19.899 --> 23:22.133
- Hey, thanks.
- Now, I'm excited, what's his name again?

23:22.135 --> 23:25.302
- His name is Sterling.
- We used to have a cat named sterling.

23:25.304 --> 23:26.570
[laughter]

23:27.472 --> 23:30.074
- [whistling]
- Oh!

23:30.375 --> 23:32.343
[Francis] Hi baby!

23:32.345 --> 23:36.280
The first thing I always look
for, for an animal for our program,

23:36.282 --> 23:37.248
is someone that needs a home.

23:37.250 --> 23:38.582
Hi, handsome.

23:38.717 --> 23:41.252
<i>Most of the animals at the
attractable animal building</i>

23:41.254 --> 23:44.321
<i>came to us pretty opportunistically.
We didn't seek them out.</i>

23:44.323 --> 23:45.823
<i>You know,
who was injured in the wild?</i>

23:45.825 --> 23:47.825
<i>Who didn't work out
in another program?</i>

23:47.827 --> 23:51.395
Sterling was raised
by the bird department.

23:51.397 --> 23:53.898
<i>And because of that,
he was imprinted on people,</i>

23:53.900 --> 23:55.733
<i>so he couldn't
go back to the flock.</i>

23:55.735 --> 24:00.004
So, we could give him a home, we
could educate the public about spoonbills.

24:00.006 --> 24:03.307
The ecology, their
environmental stresses they face.

24:03.309 --> 24:06.944
[Jim] Does he know he's a bird?
Or does he think he's a person?

24:06.946 --> 24:10.147
- I think that he thinks we're spoonbills.
- [laughter]

24:10.149 --> 24:13.451
He does a lot of those sort
of specific social behaviors,

24:13.453 --> 24:16.153
like, he'll preen, he'll flap
around, he'll play in a way

24:16.155 --> 24:17.922
that he would interact
with other birds.

24:17.924 --> 24:20.391
- [Jim] Does he come out or...
- [Francis] Oh, absolutely.

24:20.393 --> 24:22.026
- Go ahead and let him out.
- Yeah, sure.

24:22.028 --> 24:23.227
You want to come play, bud?

24:23.962 --> 24:25.229
Hey, buddy!

24:27.065 --> 24:30.501
- I love that noise!
- How are you, handsome?

24:32.070 --> 24:35.072
- Let's go down buddy. Hey bud!
- There you go.

24:35.074 --> 24:36.507
[Kathleen] How old
is he now, around?

24:36.509 --> 24:38.943
[Francis] He's a couple of
months, I want to say, four or five?

24:38.945 --> 24:40.544
- Oh, you're a youngster.
- Yeah.

24:41.179 --> 24:42.546
What're you doing my friend?

24:43.114 --> 24:44.515
That bill is so cool.

24:45.016 --> 24:48.719
Hello my love. Hi.

24:48.721 --> 24:52.790
[Jim] I think it's really important to
have birds like this in the program

24:52.792 --> 24:55.092
because a lot of people
that come to the zoo,

24:55.094 --> 24:58.095
don't necessarily
come to the zoo to see birds.

24:58.097 --> 25:00.831
Like this guy.
Who knows about a spoonbill?

25:00.833 --> 25:05.436
When you can present them with a
really cool bird that has a personality,

25:05.438 --> 25:07.671
it's a great way to get people
interested in birds.

25:11.142 --> 25:12.476
[laughter]

25:12.711 --> 25:15.346
- [Jim] You can see he's going to approach people.
- You're right.

25:15.348 --> 25:17.548
You're not can have an issue
with that.

25:18.283 --> 25:20.551
[Kathleen] And he's cool!
[laughs]

25:20.553 --> 25:24.955
<i>Sterling, I think, is going to be an
ambassador animal pretty quickly.</i>

25:24.957 --> 25:29.159
<i>So we'll see how he adapts and then
once he's used to his new surroundings,</i>

25:29.161 --> 25:31.495
his new home, we'll bring him
into the classroom.

25:31.497 --> 25:33.797
Nice to meet you!
[Laughs]

25:33.799 --> 25:35.332
[bird quacks]

25:35.334 --> 25:39.703
[Sara] We're excited that we can start
introducing her to our male, Artemis.

25:39.705 --> 25:42.706
Possibly love at first sight,
we'll see how it goes.

25:44.342 --> 25:45.342
Careful.

25:59.724 --> 26:00.991
Hey, honey.

26:00.993 --> 26:02.960
Ready?

26:02.962 --> 26:05.062
<i>Polly has been here at the zoo
for about a month.</i>

26:05.064 --> 26:08.098
<i>And she's finished
with quarantine.</i>

26:08.100 --> 26:13.037
So, we're excited that we can start
introducing her to our male, Artemis.

26:16.641 --> 26:19.877
You're the most handsome.

26:19.879 --> 26:23.347
<i>This'll be the first time Polly and
Artemis can actually see each other.</i>

26:23.349 --> 26:26.517
<i>If you put them together right
away, you could have an issue.</i>

26:26.519 --> 26:29.687
So we're gonna do intros between
what is called a 'howdy door.'

26:29.689 --> 26:32.890
<i>So it's just a mesh door so they
can see other, smell each other,</i>

26:32.892 --> 26:37.294
<i>interact a little bit, but not physically
contact each other too much.</i>

26:39.698 --> 26:42.666
Possibly love at first sight.
We'll see how it goes.

26:43.301 --> 26:44.468
Are you ready?

26:53.078 --> 26:54.445
She's kinda looking over.

26:55.213 --> 26:56.447
Hey, sweet flower.

26:57.515 --> 26:59.383
You don't even wanna know
what's over there?

27:01.219 --> 27:02.553
You gonna go down?

27:05.390 --> 27:07.358
He's a little more interested.

27:09.694 --> 27:13.397
<i>We might hear some vocalizing,
see some hair standing up.</i>

27:13.399 --> 27:16.133
But, I'm hoping we won't see
anything aggressive,

27:16.135 --> 27:18.068
or anything
that would be concerning.

27:18.070 --> 27:21.705
<i>Like, alarm calling
or start banging at the mesh.</i>

27:23.341 --> 27:24.942
Is he doing anything, Sara?

27:28.380 --> 27:29.647
[Sara] We've got movement.

27:31.282 --> 27:33.317
There you go.

27:33.319 --> 27:36.553
She's moving over there now.
She's at the door.

27:37.489 --> 27:39.156
And she's looking in.

27:42.927 --> 27:45.095
[Sara] He's being
ever so cautious.

27:49.267 --> 27:52.102
- Is that him or her?
- That's him.

27:52.104 --> 27:53.937
[Sara]
And she just started though.

27:54.939 --> 27:56.640
Who's that?

27:58.009 --> 28:00.711
<i>We've heard a little bit of
vocalizing, which is typical.</i>

28:00.713 --> 28:04.415
Nothing too crazy and that's
just totally normal.

28:04.417 --> 28:06.250
Just a hey, who are you?

28:11.389 --> 28:13.490
Yeah there you go.
Take a break.

28:15.994 --> 28:17.961
Want your carrots?

28:17.963 --> 28:21.298
- Even just her coming down and eating with everyone is...
- Yeah.

28:21.300 --> 28:23.067
[Sara] Big step for you honey.

28:25.603 --> 28:28.939
<i>We'll continue with the visual
introductions through the mesh.</i>

28:28.941 --> 28:33.043
Then we'll move forward with actually
putting the two animals together.

28:33.945 --> 28:35.279
[Jessica] This is so cute.

28:35.980 --> 28:39.283
We may have made
a love connection.

28:42.387 --> 28:45.122
- Look!
- [children chattering]

29:03.775 --> 29:05.175
[Ken] Hey goober.

29:11.149 --> 29:13.283
This is Sterling,
our African spoonbill.

29:13.285 --> 29:16.120
We kinda found him cold and
on the ground in the exhibit.

29:16.122 --> 29:18.155
And so for his safety in itself,

29:18.157 --> 29:21.525
we had to bring him to World
of Birds to be hand raised.

29:23.962 --> 29:25.229
Come on out, buddy.

29:27.165 --> 29:30.367
There you go. Come on.
Come over here.

29:30.369 --> 29:34.104
Today Sterling is gonna be going
over to the attractable animal building.

29:34.106 --> 29:36.306
Why don't you come up over here?

29:38.810 --> 29:40.177
I'll see if I can get him
to stand on the scale,

29:40.179 --> 29:42.179
so we can get
a nice body weight,

29:42.181 --> 29:46.350
that way when we move him, will know if
he's having some trouble if he loses weight.

29:52.157 --> 29:56.527
1.67 kg. That's a good weight.

30:00.198 --> 30:02.599
Hey, hey, hey, right in there.

30:09.040 --> 30:12.276
<i>He's an imprinted animal, so
he's a perfect education animal.</i>

30:13.745 --> 30:15.679
<i>He's not afraid
of people at all,</i>

30:15.681 --> 30:18.148
<i>so he's charismatic,
he's big and obvious,</i>

30:18.150 --> 30:21.118
<i>and he's got the really cool
adaptation with his nice, wide bill.</i>

30:21.120 --> 30:24.655
<i>So, an education setting is
really a perfect thing for him.</i>

30:30.695 --> 30:32.763
It's always
what were looking for, right?

30:32.765 --> 30:36.433
<i>It's always a win whenever we can
find the best situation for an animal.</i>

30:36.435 --> 30:39.036
<i>Whether that's on exhibit,
in another zoo,</i>

30:39.038 --> 30:41.705
<i>or in another
department's areas.</i>

30:41.707 --> 30:44.975
<i>I think a lot of the keepers are going to
miss Sterling when he moves on, you know?</i>

30:44.977 --> 30:47.778
<i>He such a friendly
and charismatic animal that,</i>

30:47.780 --> 30:50.080
<i>he's a fan favorite.
We'll put it that way.</i>

30:56.187 --> 30:57.855
- [Ken] Good morning.
- Hi, how are you?

30:57.857 --> 30:58.956
I'm good.

30:58.958 --> 31:00.524
We got a friend for ya.

31:02.927 --> 31:05.462
- So, he's already eaten this morning.
- Okay.

31:05.464 --> 31:10.300
- But I'm sure he'd eat again, whenever you feed him.
- Okay.

31:10.302 --> 31:14.304
- [bird calls]
- Hello.

31:14.306 --> 31:15.439
What do you think of the set up?

31:15.441 --> 31:17.107
[Ken] The running water is key.

31:17.109 --> 31:19.343
The clean water on the top
is what's gonna

31:19.345 --> 31:21.411
- keep his feathers good.
- Yeah.

31:21.413 --> 31:24.882
And then he'll get to go outside in
the nice weather, so that'll be nice.

31:24.884 --> 31:26.950
[Ken] Yeah, that'll be
really nice for him.

31:26.952 --> 31:30.320
We waited so long for Sterling
to come here. We're very happy.

31:30.322 --> 31:31.622
It's exciting.

31:33.892 --> 31:36.860
Hey, buddy. Check it out.
New digs.

31:36.862 --> 31:39.263
-There you go.
-[Kathleen] He's so good. Look at him.

31:40.331 --> 31:43.066
- Yeah, step up there.
- Hey, Sterle!

31:43.068 --> 31:46.303
Oh he's beautiful.
He got so much bigger!

31:46.938 --> 31:48.338
He looks amazing.

31:48.340 --> 31:51.141
He's curious, he's beautiful.

31:51.143 --> 31:53.310
As soon as Sterling settles in,

31:53.312 --> 31:56.113
when we see he's eating
consistently, his weight is steady

31:56.115 --> 31:58.415
<i>and he seems at ease
in his new environment,</i>

31:58.417 --> 32:00.984
<i>we're gonna introduce the
meet and greet room at TAB.</i>

32:00.986 --> 32:02.619
Yeah, you guys
are gonna love him.

32:02.621 --> 32:05.088
<i>[Kathleen] And that'll start
with just a couple of us.</i>

32:05.090 --> 32:08.358
And then we'll start bringing
new people that he doesn't know.

32:08.360 --> 32:11.862
<i>And then hopefully we'll get
him into a program pretty soon.</i>

32:11.864 --> 32:15.032
- Looks good. Thank you.
- You're very welcome.

32:15.034 --> 32:16.800
- We'll leave him settled for a little bit.
- Yeah.

32:16.802 --> 32:22.306
- Bye Sterle. Bye Ho.
- [bird calls]

32:22.308 --> 32:25.709
<i>[Micah] Creating a dynamic
exhibit is making it look like</i>

