is making it look like something
that is kind of plucked from the wild.

33:40.886 --> 33:45.322
Once the snakes are in, that
should be really just, the ribbon on top.

33:46.124 --> 33:48.525
Okay. I'm gonna do
the male first.

33:55.967 --> 33:59.136
<i>When I started here
as a full time keeper,</i>

33:59.138 --> 34:03.340
<i>working with snakes was probably
the part that I was most nervous about.</i>

34:03.342 --> 34:07.144
<i>Especially working with large
snakes and venomous snakes.</i>

34:07.146 --> 34:10.013
Oh, she is heavier.

34:15.686 --> 34:18.488
<i>But over time, and as I
learned more about them,</i>

34:18.490 --> 34:21.224
<i>and as they gained skill
and experience,</i>

34:21.226 --> 34:23.660
it's probably
my favorite part of the job.

34:24.762 --> 34:26.963
Just really,
really beautiful snakes.

34:36.074 --> 34:37.808
<i>[Don] This is the first time
in ten years</i>

34:37.810 --> 34:40.677
<i>we've had Mang vipers
on exhibit at the Bronx Zoo.</i>

34:40.679 --> 34:42.212
It's great having them
out on exhibit

34:42.214 --> 34:45.482
and seeing them
do some natural behaviors.

34:46.918 --> 34:51.154
The beauty and diversity of reptiles
and amphibians around the globe,

34:51.156 --> 34:53.990
is something that people
should appreciate.

34:53.992 --> 34:56.159
And if they don't ever
get to see these things,

34:56.161 --> 34:58.228
they may not have
that appreciation.

35:01.199 --> 35:04.701
<i>I see these animals almost on
a daily basis when I'm working.</i>

35:04.703 --> 35:07.804
<i>They're not a species you
would normally see every day.</i>

35:07.806 --> 35:12.442
So, I feel really fortunate that I get to
work with them and interact with them.

35:24.555 --> 35:27.324
- Look at the monkeys!
- Do you see the monkeys?

35:31.395 --> 35:33.096
What do you think Polly?

35:34.332 --> 35:36.867
[Sara] You guys ready?

35:36.869 --> 35:41.071
<i>So today we're gonna be putting
Polly in with Artemis for the first time.</i>

35:41.073 --> 35:44.040
Having a full introduction,
no barriers between them.

35:44.775 --> 35:46.176
[laughter]

35:47.945 --> 35:49.579
[Jessica] He's gonna go out.
Look at him.

35:53.684 --> 35:55.585
Polly, you might wanna
turn around.

35:56.888 --> 35:58.288
Here he comes.

36:01.392 --> 36:02.993
[Sara] Gonna go see him?

36:02.995 --> 36:05.395
- Oh, I did not expect that.
- I know.

36:05.696 --> 36:07.497
Wow.

36:07.499 --> 36:10.967
<i>[Sara] Surprisingly, Polly was
the one to initiate the contact at first.</i>

36:10.969 --> 36:14.604
Artemis was a little
distracted by other things.

36:14.606 --> 36:18.141
[Sarah] Not too persistent, I
mean, he's definitely interested.

36:18.442 --> 36:20.143
[laughter]

36:22.513 --> 36:24.281
[Sarah] He's just gonna
hold her tail. [laughs]

36:24.283 --> 36:27.217
- What are you gonna do with that?
- [laughter]

36:27.219 --> 36:30.320
- [Jessica] It's a very gentle kind of swatting.
- [Sara] I know, right?

36:30.322 --> 36:33.156
It's like, just go that way.

36:34.892 --> 36:38.261
<i>The swatting definitely is a,
"I don't want you doing that."</i>

36:38.263 --> 36:44.935
And just give them a warning. So,
what we're seeing is very mild aggression.

36:44.937 --> 36:47.971
[Sarah] He's being good. I mean,
you want him to be interested.

36:47.973 --> 36:49.839
- So...
- [Sara] Right.

36:49.841 --> 36:53.476
[Jessica] So, I think they're just kinda
trying to figure each other out right now.

36:53.478 --> 36:55.845
So, were just gonna err
on the side of caution,

36:55.847 --> 36:57.547
since this is the first
introduction.

36:57.549 --> 37:00.450
And split them
when we have the opportunity.

37:01.452 --> 37:02.953
[Sara] Come here, Polly!

37:04.121 --> 37:07.624
Want to shift over?
And she's in.

37:08.926 --> 37:10.060
There, you can have that.

37:10.062 --> 37:12.028
[Sarah] That was exciting!

37:12.030 --> 37:15.565
- I don't think breeding will be too difficult.
- Yeah, apparently.

37:15.567 --> 37:18.568
[Sarah] When she is receptive,
we should be golden, yeah.

37:21.739 --> 37:23.106
Head on out bub.

37:31.015 --> 37:33.316
- [woman] Oh, there she goes!
- [Sarah] Good girl.

37:37.154 --> 37:41.992
Polly's inspecting the perch
and the nesting area.

37:43.828 --> 37:46.096
Kinda smelling everything,
checking it out.

37:46.098 --> 37:48.465
I'm sure it smells
like our male, Artemis.

37:51.269 --> 37:53.837
[Jessica]
Finding her high spot.

37:53.839 --> 37:57.307
<i>Having Polly here, at the
Bronx Zoo, is exciting for us</i>

37:57.309 --> 38:02.946
<i>because it allows us to be a part of
the collective effort in helping to sustain</i>

38:02.948 --> 38:05.248
<i>the Matschie's
tree-kangaroo population.</i>

38:05.250 --> 38:06.983
[chuckle] She's cute.

38:06.985 --> 38:09.019
<i>Which is very important,</i>

38:09.021 --> 38:14.424
because the wild population is
threatened by primarily habitat loss.

38:14.426 --> 38:19.663
<i>And so as that population
faces these ongoing threats,</i>

38:19.665 --> 38:21.298
<i>and the possibility
of extinction,</i>

38:21.300 --> 38:24.067
<i>it is really important that
everybody combine their efforts</i>

38:24.069 --> 38:28.104
to try to save this species,
in zoos.

38:28.106 --> 38:32.008
-[Sara] Careful.
-[Jessica] She's cute. No doubt about that.

38:33.678 --> 38:36.513
[Kathleen] We don't like to
spring anything new on an animal.

38:36.515 --> 38:38.515
Sterle! Hey, Buddy!

38:40.184 --> 38:41.484
[Jim] What are you doing?

38:41.486 --> 38:44.220
[Kira] With his feathers
this color, you guys match.

38:44.222 --> 38:45.288
[laughter]

38:55.333 --> 38:56.666
[Kira] Hey, handsome.

38:57.702 --> 39:00.270
Do you wanna go in the
classroom? Come here buddy.

39:00.971 --> 39:02.272
Okay, you ready? Let's go.

39:03.774 --> 39:06.242
Watch your head, bud.
Go on in, good job.

39:07.912 --> 39:10.013
<i>We're gonna bring Sterling
into the classroom</i>

39:10.015 --> 39:13.283
to start acclimating
him to doing encounters.

39:14.085 --> 39:15.318
You ready buddy?

39:19.590 --> 39:20.523
[Kathleen] Sterle!

39:22.393 --> 39:23.760
Okay.

39:23.762 --> 39:26.363
<i>[Kathleen] We don't like to
spring anything new on an animal.</i>

39:26.365 --> 39:28.698
<i>We like them to get used to it
at their pace.</i>

39:28.700 --> 39:30.900
<i>What we're gonna look for
today is,</i>

39:30.902 --> 39:34.270
you know, is he confident, is he
exploring? Does he look at ease?

39:35.072 --> 39:37.040
Just, making sure
he's comfortable.

39:39.276 --> 39:41.077
Hey buddy.

39:41.079 --> 39:43.179
- [Jim] Look at that.
- Oh! There he goes!

39:43.181 --> 39:46.049
- [laughter]
- [Jim] What're you doing?

39:46.051 --> 39:48.118
[Kira] I love that.
I think that's...

39:48.819 --> 39:51.788
- Hi!
- [laughter]

39:51.790 --> 39:55.458
[man] He's so trusting though, I mean, it's
a relatively new environment, you know?

39:55.460 --> 39:58.461
I mean, even us, we're all
relatively new to him,

39:58.463 --> 40:01.331
and he still very comfortable
with us, which I like.

40:02.800 --> 40:04.968
<i>[Kathleen] He's exploring,
he's investigating.</i>

40:04.970 --> 40:07.036
<i>When you see him
with his bill down,</i>

40:07.038 --> 40:08.972
that's how
they would forage in the wild,

40:08.974 --> 40:10.540
they would search for food.

40:11.976 --> 40:15.145
[Jim] They have a lot of
sensory receptors in their beaks,

40:15.147 --> 40:17.247
so when they're going
like this in shallow water,

40:17.249 --> 40:18.948
they can feel for things to eat.

40:18.950 --> 40:21.384
So I mean, he doesn't have
hands like we do.

40:21.386 --> 40:23.987
So, he uses that beak
to feel around.

40:24.889 --> 40:27.090
He's a neat bird.

40:27.092 --> 40:31.828
- I don't think he would mind larger groups of people.
- [Kathleen] No.

40:31.830 --> 40:34.364
[man] This is probably the most
he's experienced in one setting,

40:34.366 --> 40:35.765
and he's doing pretty well.

40:35.767 --> 40:37.000
Think this'll be a big hit.

40:37.002 --> 40:39.335
[Kathleen] So, when
do you think public programs?

40:39.337 --> 40:42.038
I think he's certainly ready.

40:44.108 --> 40:45.942
[Kira] With his feathers
this color, you guys match.

40:45.944 --> 40:49.145
[laughter]

40:49.147 --> 40:52.715
<i>[Jim] I think the people that come for
the encounters will really like Sterling.</i>

40:52.717 --> 40:56.352
<i>Mainly for the reason that
they'll be in a space with a bird</i>

40:56.354 --> 40:59.055
that will be curious about them

40:59.057 --> 41:02.158
and choose to interact
with them and engage them.

41:02.160 --> 41:03.693
He wants to see what's up.

41:03.928 --> 41:06.696
<i>I think a lot of times you go
near the bird, the bird flies away.</i>

41:06.698 --> 41:09.065
<i>But when you're
in a situation like this,</i>

41:09.067 --> 41:11.267
it's a totally
different experience.

41:11.269 --> 41:13.870
- What are you doing?
- [Kathleen] He's curious about it.

41:13.872 --> 41:16.806
Sterling's story
started off a little sad.

41:16.808 --> 41:19.309
Come on Bud.
Come on Sterling.

41:19.311 --> 41:22.712
But the best end for any of our
animals is just for them to be happy.

41:23.214 --> 41:24.914
[man] Nice job.

41:25.115 --> 41:29.118
[Kathleen] Sterling is happy. He identifies
with people, and we are happy with him.

41:29.120 --> 41:30.887
So, it's a very good end to
the story.

41:30.889 --> 41:33.323
And we get to share his story
with visitors.

41:33.325 --> 41:34.724
[Kira] You did so good!

41:36.393 --> 41:37.660
Who's a good boy?
